The bacterium, <i>Tersicoccus phoenicis, </i>was named to reference its discovery in clean rooms (“Tersi”, Latin for clean), its cell shape (“Coccus”, meaning berry in Greek), and the Phoenix Mars lander that engineers worked on in the room at Kennedy Space Center where it originally turned up. In the image above, each of the bacterial cells is about one micrometer, or micron, across (about 0.00004 inch).   
In 2013, NASA discovered a bacteria evading its most stringent disinfections. Scientists just figured out how it does it.&nbsp;

